05489nam a22010335i 9780520975064DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202020cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2019052137  a97805209750647 a10.1525/97805209750642doi  a(DE-B1597)551670  a(OCoLC)1120085181  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aHV640.5.V5bL56 2020 4aHV640.5.V5bL57 2020 7aHIS0480002bisacsh04a362.87089/959222231 aLipman, Jana K., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIn Camps :bVietnamese Refugees, Asylum Seekers, and Repatriates /cJana K. Lipman. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2020  a1 online resource (328 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCritical Refugee Studies ;v100tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1. "Give Us a Ship": The Vietnamese Repatriate Movement on Guam, 1975 -- t2. To "Shoot" or to "Shoo": Vietnamese in Malaysia, 1975-1979 -- t3. A Model Camp -- t4. Hong Kong: Deterrence, Detention, and Repatriation, 1980-1989 -- t5. "Protest against Forced Repatriation!": Humanitarianism and Human Rights in Hong Kong, 1989-1997 -- t6. Palawan and Diasporic Imaginaries, 1996-2005 -- tEpilogue -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAfter the US war in Vietnam, close to 800,000 Vietnamese left the country by boat, survived, and sought refuge throughout Southeast Asia and the Pacific. This is the story of what happened in the camps. In Camps raises key questions that remain all too relevant today: Who is a refugee? Who determines this status? And how does it change over time? From Guam to Malaysia and the Philippines to Hong Kong, In Camps is the first major work on Vietnamese refugee policy to pay close attention to host territories and to explore Vietnamese activism in the camps and the diaspora. This book explains how Vietnamese were transformed from de facto refugees to individual asylum seekers to repatriates. Ambitiously covering people on the ground-local governments, teachers, and corrections officers-as well as powerful players such as the UN High Commissioner for Refugees and the US government, Jana Lipman shows that the local politics of first asylum sites often drove international refugee policy. Unsettling most accounts of Southeast Asian migration to the US, In Camps instead emphasizes the contingencies inherent in refugee policy and experiences.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aRefugee campsxPolitical aspectsy20th century. 0aRefugeeszVietnamy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Asia / Southeast Asia.2bisacsh  aactivism.  aactivists.  aasian migration.  aasylum seekers.  aasylum.  abataan.  aborder.  acommunism.  adiaspora.  agovernment.  aguam.  ahistory.  ahong kong.  aimmigration.  ainternational refugee policy.  ainternational relations.  amalaysia.  aphilippines.  apolitical science.  arefugee camps.  arefugee policy.  arefugee.  arefugees.  arepatriates.  asoutheast asia.  asoutheast asian migration.  aun high commissioner for refugees.  avietnam war.  avietnam.  avietnamese activism.  avietnamese refugee.  avietnamese.  awar.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020 Englishz978311070473008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020z9783110704525oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press Frontlist eBook-Package 2020z9